We have proved that there exists a pair $P$ and $N$ such that

$P$ is positive;

$N$ is negative;

$$
P \cup N = X \text{ and } P \cap N = \varnothing.
$$

Suppose that $(P', N')$ is another such pair

Since $P \setminus P' \subset P \cap N'$, $P \setminus P'$ is null.

Since $P' \setminus P \subset P' \cap N$, $P' \setminus P$ is null.

