Definition. The decomposition $X = P \cup N$ of $X$ as the disjoint union of a positive set $P$ and a negative set $N$ is called a Hahn decomposition for $\nu$.

Two signed measures $\mu$ and $\nu$ on $(X, \mathcal{M})$ are said to be mutually singular ($\mu$ is singular with respect to $\nu$, or vice versa) if there exists $E, F \in \mathcal{M}$ such that

$$
E \cup F = X \quad \text{and} \quad E \cap F = \varnothing,
$$

where $E$ is null for $\nu$ and $F$ is null for $\nu$. This is symbolically expressed as $\mu \perp \nu$.

