3.4 The Jordan decomposition theorem If $\nu$ is a signed measure, there exist unique positive and negative measures $\nu^{+}$ and $\nu^{-}$ such that

$$
\nu = \nu^{+} - \nu^{-} \text{ and } \nu^{+} \perp \nu^{-}.
$$

Proof. **Existence**: Let $X = P \cup N$ be a Hahn decomposition. Define

$$
\nu^{+}(E) = \nu(E \cap P) \quad \text{and} \quad \nu^{-}(E) = -\nu(E \cap N).
$$

Then

$$
\nu = \nu^{+} - \nu^{-} \quad \text{and} \quad \nu^{+} \perp \nu^{-}.
$$

**Uniqueness**: Suppose

$$
\nu = \mu^{+} - \mu^{-}, \quad \mu^{+}(F) = \mu^{-}(E) = 0, \quad E \cup F = X, \quad E \cap F = \emptyset.
$$

Then $X = E \cup F$ is a Hahn decomposition, and $P \triangle E(= N \triangle F)$ is null for $\nu$. Hence

$$
\mu^{+}(A) = \nu(A \cap E) = \nu^{+}(A) \quad \text{for all } A.
$$

