Let

$$
d \lambda = d v - f d \mu \quad (\lambda \text{ is positive since } f \in \mathcal{F}).
$$

We claim $\lambda \perp \mu$.

If $\lambda$ and $\mu$ are not mutually singular, then, by Lemma 3.7, their exist $E \in \mathcal{M}$ and $\epsilon &gt; 0$ such that

$$
\mu(E) &gt; 0 \text{ and } \lambda \geq \epsilon \mu \text{ on } E
$$

Hence

$$
d \lambda \geq \epsilon \chi_E d \mu, \quad \text{i.e. } d v \geq (f + \epsilon \chi_E) d \mu.
$$

Thus, $\int (f + \epsilon \chi_E) d\mu &gt; a$, which is a contradiction.

Uniqueness can be easily proved.

