3.10 Corollary If $\mu \ll \lambda$ and $\lambda \ll \mu$, then

$$
\frac{d\lambda}{d\mu} \frac{d\mu}{d\lambda} = 1 \quad \text{a.e. (w.r.t. either } \lambda \text{ and } \mu\text{)}.
$$

3.10 Proposition If $\mu_1, \ldots, \mu_n$ are measures on $(X, \mathcal{M})$, then there is a measure $\mu$ such that

$$
\mu_j \ll \mu \quad \text{for all } j = 1, \ldots, n,
$$

namely, $\mu = \mu_1 + \cdots + \nu_n$.

