Definition. The *total variation* of a complex measure $\nu$ is the positive measure $|\nu|$ determined by the property that, if $d\nu = f\,d\mu$ where $\mu$ is a positive measure, then

$$
d|\nu| = |f|\,d\mu.
$$

This is *well defined*.

(i) *Existence.* Every complex measure $\nu$ is of the form $d\nu = f\,d\mu$ for some positive measure $\mu$ and $f \in L^{1}(\mu)$.

$(\because)$ If $\nu = \nu_r + i\nu_i$, then we can take $\mu = |\nu_r| + |\nu_i|$.

