(ii) Uniqueness. Suppose $d\nu = f_{1}d\mu_{1} = f_{2}d\mu_{2}$. Let $\rho = \mu_1 + \mu_2$. Then

$$
f _ {1} \frac {d \mu_ {1}}{d \rho} d \rho = f _ {2} \frac {d \mu_ {2}}{d \rho} d \rho .
$$

Thus

$$
| f _ {1} | \frac {d \mu_ {1}}{d \rho} d \rho = | f _ {2} | \frac {d \mu_ {2}}{d \rho} d \rho , \rho \text{-a.e.}
$$

Hence

$$
| f _ {1} | d \mu_ {1} = | f _ {2} | d \mu_ {2}.
$$

Thus, the definition of $|\nu|$ is independent of the choice of $\mu$ and $f$.

(iii) Consistency. This definition agrees with the previous definition of $|\nu|$ when $\nu$ is a signed measure. In this case,

$$
d \nu = (\chi_ {P} - \chi_ {N}) d | \nu |, \leftarrow \text{previous definition}
$$

where $X = P \cup N$ is a Hahn decomposition. Note that

$$
| \chi_ {P} - \chi_ {N} | = 1.
$$

