# 3.13 Proposition

Let $\nu$ be a complex measure on $(X,\mathcal{M})$.

(a) $|\nu (E)|\leq |\nu |(E)$ for all $E\in \mathcal{M}$.

(b) $\nu \ll |\nu |$, and $\left|\frac{d\nu}{d|\nu|}\right| = 1$, $|\nu |$—a.e.

(c) $L^1 (\nu) = L^1 (|\nu |)$. If $f\in L^{1}(\nu)$, then

$$
\left| \int f d v \right| \leq \int | f | d | v |.
$$

## Proof.

(a) $|\nu (E)| = \left|\int_{E}f d\mu \right|\leq \int_{E}|f|d\mu = |\nu |(E).$

(b) By (a), $\nu \ll |\nu|$. If $d\nu = g d|\nu|$, then $d|\nu| = |g|d|\nu|$ by definition of $|\nu|$. Hence $|g| = 1$, $|\nu|$—a.e.

(c) The proof of $L^1 (\nu) = L^1 (|\nu |)$ omitted. We have

$$
\left| \int f d v \right| = \left| \int f \frac {d v}{d | v |} d | v | \right| \leq \int \left| f \frac {d v}{d | v |} \right| d | v | = \int | f | d | v |.
$$

