We claim

$$
\left(B \left(3 r _ {i _ {1}}, x _ {i _ {1}}\right) \cup \dots \cup B \left(3 r _ {i _ {k}}, x _ {i _ {k}}\right)\right) \supset K, \quad (*)
$$

which proves the lemma.

Suppose that  $(\ast)$  does not hold. Then, there exists

$$
y \in (B (r _ {1}, x _ {1}) \cup \dots \cup B (r _ {m}, x _ {m})) \setminus (B (3 r _ {i _ {1}}, x _ {i _ {1}}) \cup \dots \cup B (3 r _ {i _ {k}}, x _ {i _ {k}})).
$$

Suppose  $y \in B(r_l, x_l) \setminus (B(3r_{i_1}, x_{i_1}) \cup \dots \cup B(3r_{i_k}, x_{i_k}))$ . Choose  $\beta$  such that for  $\alpha = 1, \ldots, k$ ,

$$
r _ {i _ {\alpha}} \geq r _ {l} \quad \text {if and only if} \quad \alpha \leq \beta .
$$

Since

$$
y \neq \left(B \left(3 r _ {i _ {1}}, x _ {i _ {1}}\right) \cup \dots \cup B \left(3 r _ {i _ {\beta}}, x _ {i _ {\beta}}\right)\right) \quad \text {and} \quad y \in B \left(r _ {l}, x _ {l}\right),
$$

we have

$$
\left(B \left(r _ {i _ {1}}, x _ {i _ {1}}\right) \cup \dots \cup B \left(r _ {i _ {\beta}}, x _ {i _ {\beta}}\right)\right) \cap B \left(r _ {l}, x _ {l}\right) = \emptyset .
$$

We have either  $\beta = k$  or  $r_{\beta + 1} &lt; r_l$ , which is a contradiction.

