Definition. A measurable function $f: \mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{C}$ is called locally integrable (w.r.t the Lebesgue measure) if

$$
\int_{K} |f(x)| dx &lt; \infty \quad \text{for all compact sets } K \subset \mathbb{R}^n.
$$

Denote the space of locally integrable functions by $L_{loc}^{1}$. For $f \in L_{loc}^{1}$, $x \in \mathbb{R}^n$, and $r &gt; 0$, let

$$
(A_{r}f)(x) = \frac{1}{m(B(r, x))} \int_{B(r, x)} f(y) dy.
$$

3.16 Lemma If $f \in L_{loc}^{1}$, then $(A_{r}f)(x)$ is jointly continuous in $r$ and $x$ ($r &gt; 0$, $x \in \mathbb{R}^n$).

Proof. Note $m(S(r, x)) = 0$, where

$$
S(r, x) = \{y \in \mathbb{R}^n: |y - x| = r\}.
$$

