Let $\epsilon &gt; 0$. Choose $c$ such that $|f(x) - c| &lt; \epsilon$. Then

$$
\begin{array}{l}
\limsup_{r \to 0} \frac{1}{m(B(r, x))} \int_{B(r, x)} |f(y) - f(x)| dy \\
\leq \limsup_{r \to 0} \frac{1}{m(B(r, x))} \int_{B(r, x)} |f(y) - c| dy + |c - f(x)| \\
= |f(x) - c| + |c - f(x)| \\
&lt; 2\epsilon.
\end{array}
$$

Since $\epsilon &gt; 0$ is arbitrary,

$$
\lim_{r \to 0} \frac{1}{m(B(r, x))} \int_{B(r, x)} |f(y) - f(x)| dy = 0.
$$

