Theorem 3.22 Let $\nu$ be a regular signed or complex Borel measure on $\mathbb{R}^n$, and let

$$
d\nu = d\lambda + f\,dm
$$

be its Lebesgue-Radon-Nikodym representation. Then, for $m$-a.e. $x \in \mathbb{R}^n$,

$$
\lim_{r \to 0^+} \frac{\nu(E_r)}{m(E_r)} = f(x)
$$

for every family $\{E_r\}_{r &gt; 0}$ that shrinks nicely to $x$.

Proof. Note

$$
d|\nu| = d|\lambda| + |f|\,dm,
$$

and the regularity of $\nu$ implies the regularity of $\lambda$ and $f\,dm$. Since $f\,dm$ is regular, $f \in L_{loc}^{1}$.

By Theorem 3.21, it suffices to show the following: If $\lambda$ is regular, positive and $\lambda \perp m$, then for $m$-a.e. $x$,

$$
\lim_{r \to 0} \frac{\lambda(B(r,x))}{m(B(r,x))} = 0. \quad \left(\text{This implies } \lim_{r \to 0} \frac{\lambda(E_r)}{m(E_r)} = 0.\right)
$$

