Decompose $\mathbb{R}^n = A \cup A^c$ so that $m$ lives in $A$ and $\lambda$ lives in $A^c$. For $\eta &gt; 0$, let

$$
F = \left\{x \in A: \limsup_{r \to 0} \frac{\lambda(B(r, x))}{m(B(r, x))} &gt; \eta \right\}.
$$

Since $\lambda(F) = 0$ and $\lambda$ is regular, there exists an open set $U$ such that

$$
F \subset U \quad \text{and} \quad \lambda(U) &lt; \epsilon.
$$

For each $x \in F$, choose $r_x &gt; 0$ such that

$$
B_x \equiv B(r_x, x) \subset U \quad \text{and} \quad \frac{\lambda(B_x)}{m(B_x)} &gt; \eta.
$$

Note that

$$
F \subset V \equiv \bigcup_{x \in F} B_x \subset U.
$$

If $c &lt; m(F)$, then by Lemma 3.15, there exist disjoint $B_{x_1}, \ldots, B_{x_j}$ such that

$$
\frac{c}{3^n} &lt; \sum_{j=1}^{J} m(B_{x_j}) &lt; \frac{1}{\eta} \sum_{j=1}^{J} \lambda(B_{x_j}) \leq \frac{1}{\eta} \lambda(U) &lt; \frac{\epsilon}{\eta}.
$$

Hence, $m(F) = 0$.

