Since

$$
G(x + h) - G(x) = \begin{cases} \mu_G((x, x + h]), &amp; h &gt; 0, \\ -\mu_G((x + h, c]), &amp; h &lt; 0, \end{cases}
$$

Theorem 3.22 implies

$$
G'(x) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{1}{h} (G(x + h) - G(x)) = f(x) \quad \text{for } m\text{-a.e. } x.
$$

Let $H(x) = G(x) - F(x)$. We will show that $H'(x)$ exists and equals zero a.e.

Let $\{x_j\}$ be an enumeration of points at which $H \neq 0$. Then, $H(x_j) &gt; 0$ and

$$
\sum_{j: |x_j| &lt; N} H(x_j) &lt; F(N) - F(-N) &lt; \infty.
$$

Hence, the measure $\mu = \sum_{j=1}^{\infty} H(x_j) \delta_{x_j}$ is finite on every compact set. By

Theorems 1.16 and 1.18, the measure $\mu$ is regular. Since $\mu \perp m$, by Theorem 3.22, for $m$-a.e $x$,

$$
\limsup_{h \to \infty} \left| \frac{H(x + h) - H(x)}{h} \right| \leq 4 \limsup_{h \to 0} \frac{\mu((x - 2|h|, x + 2|h|))}{4|h|}.
$$

Therefore, $H'(x) = 0$ for $m$-a.e.$x$.

