# Definition

(i)  $F:\mathbb{R}\to \mathbb{C}$  is absolutely continuous if, for every  $\epsilon &gt;0$  , there exists  $\delta &gt;0$  such that  $\sum_{j = 1}^{n}|F(b_j) - F(a_j)| &lt;   \epsilon$  for every finite set of disjoint intervals  $(a_{1},b_{1}),\ldots ,(a_{n},b_{n})$  with  $\sum_{j = 1}^{n}(b_{j} - a_{j}) &lt;   \delta .$

(ii)  $F:[a,b]\to \mathbb{C}$  is absolutely continuous ( $F$  is absolutely continuous on  $[a,b]$ ) if, for every  $\epsilon &gt;0$ , there exists  $\delta &gt;0$  such that  $\sum_{j = 1}^{n}|F(b_j) - F(a_j)| &lt; \epsilon$  for every finite set of disjoint intervals  $(a_1,b_1),\ldots ,(a_n,b_n)$  in  $[a,b]$  with  $\sum_{j = 1}^{n}(b_j - a_j) &lt; \delta$ .

