Proposition 3.32 Let $F \in NBV$. Then, $F$ is absolutely continuous if and only if $\mu_F \ll m$.

Proof Note: (i) $F$ is absolutely continuous if and only if $T_F$ is absolutely continuous; (ii) $\mu_F \ll m$ if and only if $|\mu_F| \ll m$. (Furthermore, $|\mu_F| = \mu_{T_F}$ by Theorem 3.29.)

Therefore, the proposition can be restated as $T_F$ is absolutely continuous if and only if $\mu_{T_F} \ll m$. WLOG, we can assume that $F$ is increasing.

$(\Leftarrow)$ Let $\epsilon &gt; 0$ be given. By Theorem 3.5, there exists $\delta &gt; 0$ such that

$$
\mu_F(E) &lt; \epsilon \quad \text{if } m(E) &lt; \delta.
$$

Hence, if $(a_1, b_1), \ldots, (a_k, b_k)$ are disjoint and $\sum_{j=1}^{k} (b_j - a_j) &lt; \delta$, then

$$
\sum_{j=1}^{k} (F(b_j) - F(a_j)) = \sum_{j=1}^{k} \mu_F((a_j, b_j]) = \mu_F\left(\bigcup_{j=1}^{k} (a_j, b_j]\right) &lt; \epsilon.
$$

$(\Rightarrow)$ Let $m(E) = 0$. For given $\epsilon &gt; 0$, there is $\delta &gt; 0$ such that

$$
\sum_{j=1}^{k} (F(b_j) - F(a_j)) &lt; \epsilon \quad \text{if } (a_1, b_1), \ldots, (a_k, b_k) \text{ are disjoint and } \sum_{j=1}^{k} (b_j - a_j) &lt; \delta.
$$

Since the Lebesgue measure $m$ is regular, there is an open set $U$ such that $E \subset U$ and $m(U) &lt; \delta$. Express $U$ as a countable union of disjoint intervals: $U = \cup_{j=1}^{\infty}(a_j, b_j)$. Then

$$
\mu_F(E) \leq \mu_F(U) = \lim_{k \to \infty} \mu_F\left(\bigcup_{j=1}^{k} (a_i, b_i)\right) \leq \lim_{k \to \infty} \sum_{j=1}^{k} (F(b_j) - F(a_j)) &lt; \epsilon.
$$

