Definition. A complex Borel measure $\mu$ on $\mathbb{R}^n$ is called *discrete* if $\mu = \sum_{j=1}^{\infty} c_j \delta_{x_j}$ for some $x_j \in \mathbb{R}^n$ and $c_j \in \mathbb{C}$.

$\mu$ is called *continuous* if $\mu(\{x\}) = 0$ for all $x \in \mathbb{R}^n$.

Remark. For any (regular) complex Borel measure $\mu$ on $\mathbb{R}^n$, let

$$
\mu = \mu_s + \mu_{ac}
$$

be the Lebesgue decomposition. Furthermore, $\mu_s$ can be decomposed as

$$
\mu_s = \mu_d + \mu_{sc}.
$$

Hence, any (regular) complex Borel measure on $\mathbb{R}^n$ can be written uniquely as

$$
\mu = \mu_d + \mu_{ac} + \mu_{sc}.
$$

