# Theorem 3.36 (Integration by parts)

If $F, G \in NBV$ and at least one of them is continuous, then, for

$$
\begin{array}{l}
-\infty &lt; a &lt; b &lt; \infty, \\
\int_{(a,b]} F \, dG + \int_{(a,b]} G \, dF = F(b)G(b) - F(a)G(a).
\end{array}
$$

Proof. WLOG, we assume that $F$ is increasing, and $G$ is continuous and increasing. Let

$$
\Omega = \{(x, y) : a &lt; x \leq y &lt; b\}.
$$

We use Fubini's theorem to compute $\mu_F \times \mu_G(\Omega)$ in two ways:

$$
\begin{array}{l}
\mu_F \times \mu_G(\Omega) = \int_{(a,b]} \int_{(a,y]} dF(x) \, dG(y) = \int_{(a,b]} [F(y) - F(a)] \, dG(y) \\
= \int_{(a,b]} F \, dG - F(a)[G(b) - G(a)],
\end{array}
$$

and since $G(x) = G(x-)$

$$
\begin{array}{l}
\mu_F \times \mu_G(\Omega) = \int_{(a,b]} \int_{[x,b]} dG(y) \, dF(x) = \int_{(a,b]} [G(b) - G(x)] \, dF(x) \\
= G(b)[F(b) - F(a)] - \int_{(a,b]} G \, dF.
\end{array}
$$

Subtracting these two equations, we obtain the desired result.

Bara Kim 2026, Spring, Korea University
